post_text:
Applause needed for Snohomish High School student Kun Kim who has been named a National Merit Scholarship program semifinalist!

Kun joins roughly 16,000 other students nationwide who had the highest scores on the 2019 PSAT, a standardized test taken by high school juniors that helps qualify them for the award. About 1.5 million juniors took the test in 2019. About 90% of semifinalists nationwide will be named finalists in February; of those, about 7,600 will go on to receive scholarships that together total more than $30 million.

September is Suicide Prevention Month and today is World Suicide Prevention Day.

Suicide is the second leading cause of death for children, adolescents, and young adults age 5-to-24-year-old. If you or someone you know needs help, the below link contains valuable resources and information.

The National Suicide Prevention Lifeline (phone number 1-800-273-8255) provides 24/7, free and confidential support for people in distress, prevention and crisis resources for you or your loved ones. More information and resources are also available at www.sno.wednet.edu/suicideprevention

This is a reminder that all district families are needed to access their Skyward/Family Access by TOMORROW (Thursday, August 20) to indicate which learning model you will select for each child in your household as we kick off the 2020-2021 school year. Parents/guardians will need to login to Skyward/Family Access through the parent/guardian account (not the student account), and will need to make a choice for each child in the household. This information is critically needed as we prepare for the start of school.

Learning model options are 100% online instruction with teachers from your child’s home/traditional school, our Parent Partnership Program for homeschool students and families, Apex Online Learning or Running Start.

More information about each option is available on the district’s website at www.sno.wednet.edu/reopening.

post_text:
The Early Childhood Education and Assistance Program, or ECEAP, is a child development program for children aged 3 or 4 and their families. Children who experience poverty, homelessness, or are living in foster or kinship care, or are adopted from foster or kinship care, as well as children receiving special education services with the school district, are prioritized.

Although the school district will start the year through remote learning, ECEAP is still enrolling students and offering family support coaching, teacher check-ins, resources, educational activities, as well as online family support groups and informational classes to help ready your child for school. Please call 360-563-4641 for more information or 360-563-4636 for more information in Spanish.

post_text:
This afternoon, all school districts in Snohomish County received a recommendation from Snohomish Health District to begin the 2020-2021 school year using a remote learning model. The Snohomish Health District shared its concerns about widespread in-person instruction this fall given the current community transmission rate data and the evolving science around COVID-19.

Earlier today after discussion at a Snohomish School District School Board meeting, the Board decided to take action on this recommendation at a special meeting scheduled for 6 p.m. on Thursday, July 30. Additional communication from the school district will be emailed to all district families after that meeting.

You can learn more about the district’s re-opening efforts at www.sno.wednet.edu/reopening. Questions and concerns can be emailed to reopening@sno.wednet.edu.

post_text:
Earlier today, all district families were emailed information that we shared regarding school this fall. Although, we do not yet have all the answers, it is important to share the discussion at this point. While we await additional guidance from the OSPI, the Washington Department of Health (DOH) and Governor Inslee, we have been planning for various scenarios. Although none of our models are final, and unanswered details remain, it shares our path forward for the upcoming school year.

The Re-Opening Committee (ROC) has formalized its Educational Offerings recommendation to the School Board, which will be considered at the School Board’s July 22 meeting. The July 17 letter from Superintendent Kultgen, ROC documents and resources from our reopening work are posted on our website at www.sno.wednet.edu/reopening.

If you have not returned your district laptop/device, please do so. Laptops/devices must be returned on one of the days below at the district’s Resource and Service Center (1601 Avenue D in Snohomish). All laptops//devices must be returned so they can receive critical reconfiguration over the summer. Laptops/devices will be received between 9 a.m. and 4 p.m. on the following days:

• Tuesday, June 30
• Wednesday, July 1
• Thursday, July 2

There will be a technology staff member available at the RSC to receive returns. Look for the tech staff member at the roll-up/garage door on the left side of the building.

When returning laptops, please return devices fully charged and bring the power cords that were provided at distribution.
text:
If you have not returned your district laptop/device, please do so. Laptops/devices must be returned on one of the days below at the district’s Resource and Service Center (1601 Avenue D in Snohomish). All laptops//devices must be returned so they can receive critical reconfiguration over the summer. Laptops/devices will be received between 9 a.m. and 4 p.m. on the following days:

• Tuesday, June 30
• Wednesday, July 1
• Thursday, July 2

There will be a technology staff member available at the RSC to receive returns. Look for the tech staff member at the roll-up/garage door on the left side of the building.

When returning laptops, please return devices fully charged and bring the power cords that were provided at distribution.

We are also fortunate that our Kids’ Café will be able to continue delivering meals throughout the summer months. Kids' Cafe summer meals begin Monday, June 29 (see previous Facebook post regarding locations and delivery times).

post_text:
Hello Families,

On this last day of school, I want to thank you for your support this past school year. None of us could have imagined when we started the year in September, that this is how the year would end. All of us, including you, had a role to play in educating our students during the challenging time.

As the year closes, I’d like to share this video highlighting two important focuses within our district as we continue our work through the summer:

• 2020-2021 reopening plan

• Social justice, racism and equity

We’ve been called upon to meet the needs of our students, families and community while continuing to cultivate a more inclusive culture. I am confident we will be stronger as we move forward together.

Again, thank you for your ongoing support! I hope you and your families stay safe, healthy and have a great summer!

Dr. Kent Kultgen, Superintendent

Join us in saving lives! In partnership with Bloodworks Northwest, the Angel of the Winds Arena in Everett is hosting a special pop-up to give blood. All donors will receive a pair of tickets to an upcoming Seattle Storm and Everett Silvertips game!

Donating blood is an essential and encouraged activity critical to sustaining community healthcare, especially during emergencies. This one-hour donation appointment is a safe and essential action to support local hospitals and patients. Pop-up donor centers are being conducted in accordance with social distancing guidelines.

No walk-ins, guests, or people under age 16 are permitted onsite. To make your appointment, visit the link below, schedule.bloodworksnw.org or call 800-398-7888.

post_text: Due to the state’s “Safe Start” reopening guidelines, we will not be able to offer our district’s Science & Arts Academy this summer. This program has been committed to offering enriching, hands-on summer learning experiences for our students in kindergarten through 8th grade, however it is very difficult to replicate these experiences in the context of remote learning. We know this announcement is likely disappointing, but we look forward to offering this program in the summer of 2021 when conditions have changed. Questions and concerns can be directed to our district’s Teaching and Learning Services department at 360-563-7257.

The Snohomish Education Foundation (SEF) won't be able to meet together in person this year, so they are bringing our fundraising breakfast to you - "virtually!" Please join the SEF from your home on Friday, June 26, at 7:30 a.m. via Zoom as they share the good news from SEF.

• Hear from State Superintendent of Public Instruction Chris Reykdal on our ever-changing educational future.
• To register for the breakfast, visit https://sef2020breakfast.eventbrite.com/
• If you are not able to attend, but would like to donate, visit www.snoed.org/donate. Donations can be mailed to Snohomish Education Foundation, P.O. Box 1312, Snohomish, WA 98291.
• For other FAQs please visit the SEF website at www.snoed.org/breakfast.

You can be a part of this important work. We hope you are able to have coffee with the SEF on June 26! Thank you for your support of learning!

Curbside pickup available for in-stock Snohomish Aquatic Center gift shop merchandise 11 a.m. - 4 p.m., Monday through Saturday!

While the Snohomish Aquatic Center is temporarily closed for in-person shopping, we are still here for you, servicing pick-up orders. Our gift shop items make wonderful gifts. We will regularly post, update and add items in our Gift Shop Merchandise Facebook album.

To place an order email your order to swim@snohomishaquatic.com. Please include your phone number when sending your email so that we can process your order over the phone. We will be checking emails often and get back to you as soon as we are able. We will pack up your order, process your credit card over the phone and then deliver your order to your car when you arrive. We are doing everything we can to help you with your needs while keeping our community safe and healthy.

From the entire Snohomish Aquatic Center team, we thank you!

post_text: Way to go Sonic Squirrels! The Sonic Squirrels, the robotics team from Glacier Peak High School and Snohomish High School, is helping support a local volunteer group in its 3D printing and sewing parts for NIH-approved personal protective equipment (PPE) for fire, medical, first responders and more. So far the team has helped produce and distribute about 200 face masks. The printed parts they are helping create are able to be sterilized and reused. The team is also donating to a regional FIRST (an international robotics organization with programs for students K-12) fundraising campaign that is helping to raise funds for Food Lifeline. Fantastic!

As a way to honor our 2020 seniors at AIM High School, Glacier Peak High School and Snohomish High School, our district will be participating in the “Be the Light” campaign (#BeTheLightWA) that has been gaining national attention and moving through the United States. Stadium lights at Veterans Memorial Stadium (located on the Snohomish High School campus) and Glacier Peak High School will be turned on this Friday night, April 17, starting at 8:20 (20:20 military time) for 20 minutes. The lights are our way of showing support for our students and 2020 graduates.

Please note that this not an invitation to gather. School campuses remain closed, and no parking will be available. Please view the lights in compliance with Governor Inslee’s “Stay Home, Stay Healthy” guidelines.

One Snohomish - One Community

post_text:
It's #censusday2020! Please complete the census today at www.2020census.gov. It only takes 5 minutes (or less).

Census data provides critical population information that’s used by programs and agencies across the government. Census data impacts federal funding for schools, including funding for school meals programs, special education, career and technical education, and much more. Census data also determines representation in Congress. Congressional lines are redrawn at the national level once every 10 years based on Census information.

The Census asks a number of simple questions:
• How many people were living or staying in the house, as of April 1, 2020?
• Were there additional people not included in question 1?
• Is the residence a house, apartment, or mobile home?
• What is your telephone number? (Only used for official Census business)

And for each person in the house, their:
• Name
• Sex
• Age/Date of Birth
• Whether they’re of Hispanic, Latino, or Spanish origin
• Race

post_text: This morning we received a call from EvergreenHealth in Monroe asking for donations of personal protection equipment (PPE) for their medical staff as their supplies were running low with no commitments from suppliers. By 12:30 p.m. a group of district teachers and employees were able to collect and deliver 8000 gloves, dozens of eye protection googles and face shields, as well as surgical masks and gowns from the district’s Maintenance and Operations Department and Snohomish High School’s science and career and technical education classrooms. When teachers and district crew arrived to deliver the supplies, our team was met with some very excited hospital staff who loaded up their cart and were able to continue their jobs providing health care for our community. Way to go Snohomish!

During this first week of the state-mandated district closure, Kids’ Café mobile food service is providing free sack breakfasts and lunches for those who need them Monday through Friday at the following locations and times:

• Boys & Girls Club - 10:30-10:55 a.m.
• Snohomish Aquatic Center - 11-11:25 a.m.
• Emerson Elementary - 11:30-11:55 a.m.
• Snohomish High School – Noon-12:25 p.m. (truck will be at front entrance to school in the south parking lot)
• Circle H Mobile Home Park - 12:40-1 p.m.
• 3 Rivers Mobile Home Park - 11:15-11:45 a.m.
• Valley View Middle School - Noon-12:30 p.m.

Breakfast delivery service will begin on Tuesday, March 17. At daily delivery, a student will get 2 sack meals - a lunch for the current day and a breakfast to save for the next.

Please also be aware we will likely be making adjustments to our breakfast/lunch delivery schedule and locations that would take effect on Monday, March 23. We will be communicating those changes to our families next week. Thank you for your support.

post_text:
Mush! Last week, Centennial Middle School students in Staci Tuck's ELL class learned first-hand what it's like to participate in the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race held in Alaska. Tuck's unit is developing academic vocabulary through the study of geography, math, history and science. They are also exploring themes such as perseverance and leadership.

Through a district staff connection, students were able to Skype with Tom Frode Johansen, who is participating in the 2020 Iditarod race, and one of his teammates Nora Sjalin, who is a Yukon Quest participant. The real star of the learning experience was Matilda, the 3-year-old Siberian Husky who led Nora's team last week in the Yukon Quest and is participating this week with Tom in the Iditarod!

Everett Public Schools-WA
February 28 at 9:06 PM ·

To keep everyone informed, the Snohomish Health District notified us we have a confirmed case of Coronavirus, or COVID-19, at Henry M. Jackson High School. We are in ongoing communication with the Washington State Department of Health and the Snohomish Health District to determine how we should proceed.

The student is quarantined and the few students who were in contact, along with family members, are quarantined and will be tested if they develop symptoms.

In an abundance of caution the school will be closed on Monday, March 2 to allow for three full days of deep disinfecting beginning this evening through Monday.

We are taking this seriously and will keep families and community updated as we get direction from the Department of Health and Snohomish Health District.

Go to http://bit.ly/ConfirmedCoronaCaseFeb28 for letter sent to families & staff including resources.

post_text:
THURSDAY, FEBRUARY 27, MEETING

Students… launch your career in aerospace and advanced manufacturing! The Aerospace Joint Apprenticeship Committee (AJAC) and the Snohomish School District are launching the third cohort of aerospace and advanced manufacturing youth apprenticeships this spring. Join us at Youth Apprentice Night - an informational meeting will be held TOMORROW (Thursday, February 27) from 6-7:30 p.m. at the district’s Resource and Service Center (1601 Avenue D in Snohomish). Students, parents and guardians are welcome to attend the event.

AJAC Youth Apprentices will receive tuition-free college credits from a local technical college. This program is a combination of paid on-the-job training (part-time) and college-level classroom instruction. This is a no-cost program to qualified participants. Upon completion, students will receive industry recognized journey-level certification as a production technician.

Congratulations to these Glacier Peak High School students who are one step closer to joining the high ranks of National Merit Scholars!
• Richard Ahn
• Kevin Cho
• Isaac Olson
• Lauren Zarlingo

The finalists emerged from a list of about 16,000 semifinalists who qualified based on their scores in the previous year’s Preliminary SAT/National Merit Scholarship Qualifying Test, taken by about 1.6 million high school sophomores and juniors. To become finalists, students had to submit a scholarship application that reflects a strong academic record, participation in school and community activities, leadership abilities, employment and any honors or awards. National Merit Scholarship winners of 2020 will be announced April through July.

Way to go!

Thursday, January 16 - 2-Hour Delay, Buses on Inclement Weather (Snow) Routes

Snohomish School District schools will be delayed two (2) hours on Thursday, January 16. With the two-hour (2) delayed start, the following will apply:
• All regular full-day classes will be held beginning two (2) hours later than normal.
• Buses are on limited transportation (snow) routes. Please note: The times and locations on the limited transportation pdfs reflect normal pick-up times - please add two (2) hours for the two-hour school delay.
• No out-of-district transportation.
• No a.m. and/or p.m. half-day special education preschool, or ECEAP.
• No morning AIM classes.
• No zero-hour classes.
• No Sno-Isle Technical Skills Center.
• No morning elementary band.
• The Snohomish Aquatic Center will open at 8 a.m.

Learn more at www.sno.wednet.edu/weather

Please feel free to learn more about the district's decision-making process and communications in regard to inclement weather conditions by visiting www.sno.wednet.edu/weather.

In the event of inclement weather, the district office will decide whether to:
• Hold school (regular hours)
• Hold school (delayed start) - All schools will start two hours late. Buses may or may not be on limited transportation (snow) routes.
• Close school

Because we know many are getting ready for school or leaving early, we try to get these notifications out to our school community between 5:15-5:45 a.m.

We appreciate your understanding.

Jasper, one of the dogs in the University of Washington Center for Conservation Canines program, visited with some Glacier Peak High School science students earlier today and showed them how he is able to locate wildlife scat in an open area utilizing only his keen sense of smell.

The Conservation Canines program uses detection dogs to readily locate wildlife scat (feces) samples with the ability to extract a wide variety of genetic, physiological, toxicological and dietary indicators from these samples. These indicators enable scientists at the center to ascertain species abundance, distribution, resource use, and physiological health all in relation to the environmental pressure(s) the species may be encountering. Learn more about the program at https://conservationbiology.uw.edu/conservation-canines/

The Tragedy of Macbeth - Snohomish High School fall play

Performance dates:
• December 6, 7, 12 and 13 at 7 p.m.
• December 7 at 1 p.m.
• December 14 at 4 p.m.

Tickets can be purchased:
• Online at Brown Paper Tickets (https://m.bpt.me/event/4445537) for $10/each
• At the door for $13/each

Show information:
• Macbeth, a brave Scottish lord and general, receives a prophecy from a trio of witches that one day he will be crowned the King of Scotland. Consumed by ambition and spurred to action by his wife, Macbeth murders King Duncan and claims the Scottish throne as his own. His guilt and paranoia take him spiraling down a rabbit hole of ghostly apparitions and deepening madness, leading him to commit more and more murders to protect himself from enmity and suspicion. The consequent civil war swiftly lead Macbeth and Lady Macbeth to their tragic deaths.
• This play will be staged in the round, with all seating on the stage.
• Due to the on stage violence and complexity of the language, this play is not recommended for children.

Wondering what those pumpkins in the Snohomish roundabout are all about? It's to highlight the premier of the world's first animated movie made by kids - Snohomish kids!

Snohomish Story Makers presents WonderGrove's Wizard of Oz on November 9 and November 16 at the Snohomish High School Performing Arts Center! Young voice actors from Riverview Elementary and Snohomish Boys and Girls Club recently performed 15 roles for the animated characters featured in The WonderGrove production of Wizard of Oz. Students auditioned for the roles, and those selected brought each character to life through voice, character animation and story creation.

Join them as they share the story of Dorothy, a sixth grader, who is worried about going to middle school, with the audience. Together, they will follow the yellow brick road! Showtimes are on November 9 at 3 p.m. and November 16 at 5 p.m. Learn more by visiting Snohomish Story Makers Facebook page or purchase tickets to the production at https://wizofoz.bpt.me.

Wondering what those pumpkins in the Snohomish roundabout are all about? It's to highlight the premier of the world's first animated movie made by kids - Snohomish kids!

Snohomish Story Makers presents WonderGrove's Wizard of Oz on November 9 and November 16 at the Snohomish High School Performing Arts Center! Young voice actors from Riverview Elementary and Snohomish Boys and Girls Club recently performed 15 roles for the animated characters featured in The WonderGrove production of Wizard of Oz. Students auditioned for the roles, and those selected brought each character to life through voice, character animation and story creation.

Join them as they share the story of Dorothy, a sixth grader, who is worried about going to middle school, with the audience. Together, they will follow the yellow brick road! Showtimes are on November 9 at 3 p.m. and November 16 at 5 p.m. Learn more by visiting Snohomish Story Makers Facebook page or purchase tickets to the production at https://wizofoz.bpt.me.

post_text: The Glacier Peak High School/Snohomish High School robotics team, the Sonic Squirrels, traveled to San Jose, CA last weekend to compete in an invitational competition with 40 of the top teams in the western United States. The team finished qualifications ranked 11th. During alliance selections for the playoff teams, the Sonic Squirrels moved up to become the captains of the 8th seeded alliance where they chose team Code Orange from Orange County, CA, team Bear Metal from Maple Valley WA, and team Space Cookies from Mountainview, CA to form its playoff team. The Sonic Squirrels faced the top seeded alliance and were eliminated in the quarter finals. The team came away with many ideas for robot and program ideas that it can use to keep improving! Congrats!

post_text: Glacier Peak High School’s yearbook The Edge is the recipient of the 2019 Washington Journalism Education Association’s (WJEA) Yearbook Emerald Award! Only three Washington state high schools were the recipients of WJEA yearbook awards which were recently presented at the University of Washington. Graduate Kirsty Fleming was the editor-in-chief of the award-winning yearbook. This year’s yearbook editors-in-chief are Maggie Borland and Elizabeth Schwartzhoff. Teacher Annie Green is the yearbook adviser.

2019 marks the 125th anniversary of Snohomish High School and the 90th anniversary of the school's band program!

The Snohomish High School Band Boosters are planning a 90th anniversary alumni benefit concert on April 14, 2020, at Snohomish High School. Band alumni who are interested in playing at the event should contact volunteer@snohomishbandboosters.org.

Proceeds from the April 14 event will be used to help purchase a five-octave marimba for the school's band program. Watch for more details about this alumni event in the coming months.

Congratulations to these Glacier Peak High School students on being named semifinalists in the National Merit Scholarship Program! Across the nation, the National Merit Scholarship Corporation designates about 16,000 semifinalists from among nearly 1.6 million students who take the PSAT during their sophomore or junior year. Semifinalists are the highest scoring entrants in each state. They will continue on in the 2020 competition for National Merit Scholarship awards. Finalists will be announced in February 2020.
• Richard Ahn
• Lauryn Ardry
• Kevin Cho
• Isaac Olson
• Lauren Zarlingo

post_text:
This year’s Kids’ Café Summer Meal Program was a tremendous success! We served 6,877 breakfasts and 13,490 lunches (for a total of 20,367 meals) to young people from our community. Of the total meals, 9,064 were served at Snohomish High School (breakfast and lunch). Through the Mobile Kids’ Café:
• 7,721 breakfasts and lunches were delivered to our local Boys and Girls Club
• 1,224 lunches went to the Circle H Mobile Home Park
• 1,129 lunches were distributed at Three Rivers Mobile Home Park
• 1,229 lunches were served at the Snohomish Aquatic Center

We truly could not have accomplished this without the support and assistance of our community volunteers. This summer, 171 volunteers (totaling more than 855 volunteer hours) joined us in our effort to feed children and families from our community. Their help allowed us to feed children who may have otherwise gone without.

Thank you Snohomish!

post_text: More than 50 Riverview Elementary students and parents recently traveled to Hollywood to attend the world premiere of Wondergrove Media's production of the Wizard of Oz. This was a huge nationwide project that Riverview students worked on throughout the 2018-2019 school year. The students casted voice actors, created backgrounds, animated characters and recorded all the voices for the project. While in Hollywood, they participated in a two-day conference where they improved their script writing, story boarding, voice acting and sound design skills. They also got to hear from Hollywood voice legends Joey Paul Jenson and Rob Paulson. A local premiere of the project will be scheduled for early November at the Snohomish High School Performing Arts Center. Yahoo!

post_text:
This morning’s earthquake centered right here in Snohomish reminded us that the Pacific Northwest is continually at risk.

As a reminder, in the event of an earthquake you will reduce your chance of injury if you:
• DROP where you are, onto your hands and knees. This position protects you from being knocked down and also allows you to stay low and crawl to shelter if nearby.
• COVER your head and neck with one arm and hand. If a sturdy table or desk is nearby, crawl underneath it for shelter. If no shelter is nearby, crawl next to an interior wall (away from windows). Stay on your knees; bend over to protect vital organs.
• HOLD ON until shaking stops.

More safety resources are available on our district website under the Safety Reference Links and Safety Reference Materials subsections located at www.sno.wednet.edu/safety.

Special congrats to Centennial Middle School, Dutch Hill Elementary, Machias Elementary and Riverview Elementary who were recognized by state Superintendent Chris Reykdal earlier today for being named State Recognized Schools!

The Office of Superintendent of Public Instruction, State Board of Education, and Educational Opportunity Gap Oversight and Accountability Committee have created a new system of recognizing and celebrating schools’ achievement on the Washington School Improvement Framework (WSIF) measures. The new system places more emphasis on schools which are making progress closing opportunity gaps among student groups, as well as schools which have lower levels of achievement, but are seeing high levels of progress. post_text: Our district's Marine Corps JROTC hosted its annual Change of Command, Promotion and Awards Ceremony last week. More than a dozen veteran service organizations offered awards and scholarships to our cadets. They awarded $8,500 in local scholarships and three cadets received full four-year scholarships - one to the Coast Guard Academy, one to West Point and one received an NROTC scholarship to University of Washington. Of the 18 graduating seniors, 10 are headed to college, one has enlisted in the Marine Corps, and the remaining seven plan to join the workforce. Most of the cadets in the unit saw their hard work pay off and were promoted. Those promotions come with more stripes, but they also come with more responsibility. Congratulations to all!

post_text:
Amazing accomplishment! Glacier Peak High School senior Jonathan Ahrens was named a National Merit Scholarship recipient. As a National Merit Scholarship recipient, Jonathan is part of an elite group of students selected nationwide for this honor.

National Merit Scholarship recipients were selected from among the finalists in the National Merit Scholarship competition after meeting certain criteria from the sponsors. The finalists emerged from a list of about 16,000 semifinalists who qualified based on their scores in the previous year’s Preliminary SAT/National Merit Scholarship Qualifying Test, taken by about 1.6 million high school juniors. To become finalists, students had to submit a scholarship application that reflects a strong academic record, participation in school and community activities, leadership abilities, employment and any honors or awards.

High schoolers (and parents/guardians) - Do you have a school fine that must be paid by the end of the school year?

Please pay online to avoid wait times at your school bookkeeping office. Payments made for bookkeeping fines will show in real time. Payments made to the student’s food service account will be reflected within 12-24 hours. There is a $1.25 convenience fee per online transaction.

The bookkeeping office can accept cash or checks as well as credit/debit cards. Convenience fees are not charged if payment is made through the bookkeeping office.

• The link is to the online payment/Touchbase system is https://wa-snohomish.intouchreceipting.com/.
• More info on the district's online payment/TouchBase system is available at www.sno.wednet.edu/onlinepayments

All student fines must be paid by the end of the 2018-2019 school year.

Glacier Peak High School sophomore Elijah Croyle has been selected the winner of the National Association for Music Education’s (NAfME) Electronic Music Composition Competition for the 9th-12th grade category!

The NAfME Electronic Music Composition Competition recognizes outstanding compositions and highlights the effectiveness of music technology in the school curriculum. Entries are judged based on their aesthetic quality, use of electronic media, and the power of the composition.

You can listen to Elijah's composition "Give It A Week” at the link below - https://nafme.org/wp-content/files/2019/05/Give_It_A_Week_-_Remix_2-MP3.mp3

Snohomish School District added 26 new photos — at Snohomish High School.
May 20, 2019 at 3:19 PM · Snohomish, WA ·

Earlier today, Snohomish High School students packed 150,000 meals to be distributed locally and globally as part of their SHS Fight Hunger project. The campaign is a partnership between the Dream Dinners Foundation and the Snohomish High School DECA program. More than 1,000 students and community volunteers gathered to assemble non-perishable meals designed to save children in need from malnutrition in our local community and throughout the developing world.
